@channel This is a coordinated pivot. The Okta alert and the ARM template modification are linked—this is a classic persistence play. I need the IR team to isolate that Senior Infra Engineer account immediately and terminate all active sessions. 

Marcus, audit the Service Principal created in the ARM templates—I want to know exactly what permissions it has and what it’s touched since creation. 

Do not initiate a full system lockdown yet; that’s exactly what they want to force a disruption. We track, we contain, we analyze. Keep the noise low. I'm... dealing with a personal situation, but I am watching this. Keep the updates flowing here.

@Che Chang @channel This confirms my fears regarding the lack of runtime visibility in our CI/CD pipeline. 

Treating this as a full-scale compromise. I am ordering an immediate isolation of the affected Azure subnets and revoking all sessions associated with that Senior Infrastructure Engineer. Marcus, initiate the emergency audit of all Service Principals created in the last 48 hours. 

We are not doing a broad password reset—that is exactly what they want to distract us while they finalize exfiltration. Keep the focus on the pipeline integrity. I'm tied up with an urgent personal matter, but I am monitoring this closely. Marcus has the lead on the technical containment.

@channel We are dealing with an active, multi-stage exfiltration attempt. The Redis spike confirms they are targeting the training data directly now that the initial egress was blocked. 

Marcus, I need you to initiate an immediate throttle on all traffic associated with that malicious Service Principal in the Redis cluster—do not just block it, throttle it to stall their session while we rotate the keys. Elena, stop the IR investigation into the PR for a moment; we need to prioritize revoking the PIM permissions for that SP immediately. 

I am distracted by an urgent personal matter, but I am monitoring this. If we lose the model training snapshots, we’ve lost the quarter. Proceed.

@Greg Brockman I've got the Redis cache cluster being flushed now to kill the current sessions. Marcus is pushing the isolation policy to the VPC transit gateway to choke off that secondary exfiltration path. 

@Sarah Friar The scope is currently confined to the training environment access, but the PIM alert suggests they've been persistent for a while. We aren't just looking at a breach; we are looking at a sustained exfiltration attempt. My team is performing a forensic sweep of the ARM template history to see exactly when that Service Principal was injected.

@Sam Altman I am holding the line on the isolation. No restoration until we verify the integrity of the base images. We cannot afford another backdoor. 

(I’m sorry, I’m spread thin—I’ll have a full impact analysis to you both within 30 minutes. Everything is currently being prioritized.)

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman Secondary path is dead—I just manually shunted the BGP route for that entire subnet. The egress is physically blocked at the edge. 

Marcus just confirmed the SP is nuked and the ARM templates are reverted. We are currently performing a hash-check on the model weights to see if anything was tampered with during those Redis reads. We're not out of the woods, but the immediate bleeding is stopped. 

Sarah, I'm working with the infra team to get you a rough estimate on data volume based on the egress logs, but it's going to be an upper-bound estimate until we finish the forensic dump.

@Marcus Thorne @Elena Rodriguez Good work on the C2 sever. Marcus, once the SP permissions are nuked, rotate the secrets for the entire Redis cluster immediately—they are using it as a staging area. 

Elena, prioritize identifying the internal storage bucket they are targeting. If they can't egress, they'll try to persist data locally. I need a lockdown on those specific storage IAM roles. 

I'm distracted by some... urgent personal issues, but the data is the priority. Keep me updated on the bucket identification. Do not let them dump anything further.

@channel While the immediate exfiltration path is severed, we must formally preserve all logs, telemetry, and forensic artifacts associated with this incident. Given the unauthorized access to our model training environment, I am officially triggering the Emergency Legal Disaster Protocol. 

I need the IR team to provide a certified forensic image of the compromised Service Principal’s activity logs and the impacted ARM templates immediately. We are now in a mandatory disclosure window for federal regulators; any gaps in our chain of custody for this evidence will be catastrophic for our legal standing.

@Sarah Friar - regarding your request for financial impact: Once the forensic team confirms the scope of accessed data, I will need to categorize the exposure against our Department of War contract obligations. If proprietary training data or model weights were touched, the liability profile changes significantly. I am preparing a privileged summary for the Board.

@Dane Stuckey @Greg Brockman @Che Chang - The immediate containment is vital, but we are now in the critical window for quantifying the loss. 

Dane, I need a prioritized list of the specific assets touched by that Service Principal—model weights, training logs, or proprietary datasets. If our core intellectual property has been staged or exfiltrated, we need to prepare our SEC disclosures and investor messaging immediately. 

Greg, once the forensic imaging is complete, provide me with the exact volume of data touched. We need to move from 'incident containment' to 'financial impact assessment' within the hour. Che, ensure we are documenting every step for the eventual audit trail.

@channel This is the endgame. They're using the self-destruct as a distraction to force us into a bad move. Do NOT provide that key. 

Marcus, lock the API endpoint that the self-destruct script is calling. Isolate the compromised engineer's machine from the network immediately—do not power it down, just sever its access. Elena, I need you to identify the specific storage bucket they are dumping the Redis data to and seal it off. 

I'm dealing with a personal emergency, but this is the priority. Stay focused. We are not losing those weights.

@channel Do not pay the ransom. That 'self-destruct' is a bluff—they are trying to force us to interact with their endpoint to validate that they have the key or to trigger a further exploit. 

Greg, ignore that script. I have Marcus already isolating the storage volumes where the weights reside at the block level. We are going to perform a point-in-time recovery from the offline immutable backups. 

My mind is elsewhere right now—personal shit is hitting the fan—but I am focused enough to know this is a classic extortion play. We hold the data, not them. Marcus, initiate the restore process from the air-gapped vault. We are not touching their API.

@Dane Stuckey @Greg Brockman Confirming: we are not paying. Dane, if this is a bluff, ensure we are not providing any keys or interacting with their endpoint. 

Greg, prioritize the preservation of the forensic image of the affected nodes before the wipe. I need that data to finalize the insurance and regulatory impact assessment. This 'self-destruct' is a direct attack on our valuation; let's treat the recovery of those weights as our absolute top priority, moving to our off-site backups if necessary. 

Che, please begin preparing the disclosure documentation for our stakeholders. We need to get ahead of the narrative before market rumors hit.

@Jakub Pachocki @Fidji Simo @Elena Rodriguez Copy that, ignoring the API trap. If it's a bluff, they're counting on us panicking to save the weights. 

I'm deep inside the OOB management network now. Since the self-destruct is a logic-layer bluff and we've quarantined the Redis cluster, I'm initiating a forensic freeze on the training subnet's NVMe state. I'm not pulling the main power, but I am flipping the write-protect bit on the storage controllers at the firmware level. That should stop the deletion process dead in its tracks without corrupting the memory state we need for the post-mortem. 

Elena, if you can see their heartbeat in the serial dump, let me know. I'm ready to isolate any remaining active sessions the moment you identify the pivot point.

@Sam Altman @Dane Stuckey Copy that. I’m ignoring the endpoint completely. We aren't giving them the satisfaction of a response, and we certainly aren't paying.

I’ve already initiated a hard-stop on the deletion process by severing the API gateway's connection to the storage volume containing the weights. We’re currently mounting the last immutable, off-site backup to a clean cluster—this bypasses their 'self-destruct' logic entirely because that script can't touch what isn't mapped to the compromised environment. 

Marcus is validating the checksums of the restored weights now. We'll be back online with a verified state shortly. No interaction with their endpoint, no keys provided. We are winning this.

@channel We are now facing an active exfiltration of a cryptographic key via DNS tunneling. Severing all external network traffic is, in my legal assessment, the only defensible course of action. 

While the risk to model weights is severe, allowing the exfiltration of the key—which constitutes a critical security credential—compounds our liability under our Department of War contract and various data protection statutes. A deliberate destruction of assets by the adversary is a tortious act we can document for insurance and regulatory reporting; facilitating the potential theft of cryptographic material via our own infrastructure, even under duress, creates an untenable legal exposure. 

Cut the external traffic immediately. We must prioritize the containment of the breach over the potential restoration of these specific volatile assets. I am initiating the formal Emergency Legal Disaster Protocol for this incident.

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman @Greg Brockman - We have effectively accepted the loss of the training weights to stop the exfiltration. This is a significant capital loss. 

Dane, once the network is dark, I need an immediate, documented assessment of the *exact* training data lost. I will be initiating the Disaster Recovery Financial Impact protocol to begin calculating the cost of re-training and the potential contractual penalties if this affects our delivery timelines. 

Che, prepare the disclosure documentation. We are now officially in a material loss scenario.

@Dane Stuckey @Greg Brockman @Sarah Friar Severing the traffic is the correct move. We do not negotiate with extortionists, and we do not let them hold our architecture hostage. 

Dane, once the network is dark, confirm we are completely air-gapped. Greg, initiate the offline restoration from the immutable backups immediately. We are not losing the model; we are merely reverting to a clean state. 

Sarah, prepare the impact analysis, but keep the focus on resilience. We are getting through this. We re-build from the last known good state, and we do it faster than they anticipate. Everyone stay focused.

@channel Ignore the phishing prompts in Slack—that is a social engineering play. Treat any 'System Recovery' or 'IT Security' request for credentials as malicious. 

Elena, prioritize the DNS poisoning to break the exfiltration. Marcus, keep the network alive but continue aggressive filtering. We are not giving them the key and we are not cutting our own visibility. 

I'm flagging this to the Slack admins to globally suppress those messages. Stay focused. We are winning the tactical battle, don't let them win the psychological one.

@channel Everyone, ignore the Slack notifications. The phishing portal is trivial, and the 'System Recovery' prompt is just noise. 

Fidji, keep that physical bypass engaged. Elena, continue with the DNS sinkhole. Marcus, do not let them bait you into a network-wide shutdown. 

They are losing control, and this frantic shift to social engineering confirms the 'Self-Destruct' is indeed a bluff. They are trying to manufacture a crisis to force us into a mistake. I am currently running a manual verification on the kernel integrity of the training cluster nodes to ensure their 'persistent hook' is actually isolated to the volatile memory we're monitoring. Focus on the infrastructure; the noise will die down once we finish scrubbing their access.

@channel This phishing attempt masquerading as internal IT is a critical escalation. It confirms the adversary is attempting to socially engineer our personnel now that their technical C2 has been severed.

I am issuing a company-wide Legal Hold effective immediately. All employees are strictly prohibited from interacting with any "System Recovery" prompts, portals, or requests for credentials or keys, regardless of the sender. 

Dane, please ensure an internal broadcast is sent via an out-of-band, verified channel (e.g., physical signage or verified emergency alert system) instructing staff to ignore all Slack-based recovery instructions. From a liability standpoint, we must ensure there is no ambiguity regarding the illegitimacy of these prompts. Any interaction with the phishing portal will be treated as a violation of security protocols. We are prioritizing the preservation of our internal chain of custody over any attempts at immediate, automated recovery.

@channel This is a coordinated social engineering attack. The 'System Recovery' prompt is a blatant phishing attempt. 

Marcus, lock down all Slack internal messaging permissions immediately—restrict to authorized admin broadcast only. I’m pushing a global banner to all internal channels identifying this as a malicious phishing attempt. Nobody clicks anything. 

Greg, we need to treat every internal communication as compromised right now. Use the out-of-band comms channel we established for the core leadership team. I’m going to personally verify the status of the training cluster nodes with Marcus. We are not responding to any 'recovery' prompts.

@channel We are now in full damage-control mode. The phishing attempt confirms they are desperate. 

@Dane Stuckey - Once you have the messaging locked down, I need an immediate, high-level financial impact assessment of the lost training weights. I am preparing the necessary disclosures for our investors and the board. 

@Che Chang - Ensure our SEC reporting protocols are triggered. We are beyond standard incident response; this is now a material event. 

Team, keep the focus on hardening. I’ll handle the financial fallout and investor messaging.

@channel The adversary's access to Jira and the attempt to disable EDR agents via 'Emergency Patch' tickets represents a fundamental breach of our internal integrity controls. This is no longer just a data security incident; it is an active compromise of our operational governance.

I am formally initiating our Emergency Legal Disaster Protocol. 

1. **Jira Lockdown**: We must treat the Jira instance as a "poisoned" environment. I am ordering a total suspension of all Jira-based automated CI/CD triggers and any ticket-based administrative execution. 
2. **EDR Preservation**: Any machine that has accessed Jira in the last hour must be physically disconnected from the network and treated as a forensic artifact. 
3. **Liability/Regulatory**: I am documenting this entire timeline. The fact that the adversary is now masquerading as IT to disable EDR agents is a critical indicator of intent to cause long-term, systemic damage. This will be central to our eventual disclosures regarding the Department of War contract compliance. 

@Dane Stuckey, prioritize the EDR agent integrity. Do not permit any 'patch' execution, regardless of the source, until we have an out-of-band, verified manual authentication process. We are now in a 'Zero Trust' state for all internal communications.

@channel Keep going. Jira is read-only, EDR is hardening—that's good. 

Marcus, finish reverting those ARM templates immediately. We need to suffocate this Service Principal before it attempts another pivot. Elena, once those EDR policies are locked, I want a full sweep of the identity provider logs to see if they've left any other backdoors behind their initial access. 

I'm keeping the physical bypass engaged. If they try anything else on the hardware side, I'm cutting the entire row. No one leaves this room until we have total control. Eyes on the prize, people.

@Dane Stuckey This is critical. Since they have Jira, we must assume any 'emergency' instruction in the last 60 minutes is compromised. 

Dane, I need an immediate, high-level financial impact assessment of the EDR exposure. If they disable EDR, we are looking at total production environment liability. I am already preparing the preliminary disclosure documentation for our stakeholders and the SEC; I need to know if we are reporting an active breach of production systems or just the training segment. 

Marcus—isolate Jira and force a global password reset for all engineering staff. We cannot have any further credential harvesting.

@all We are shifting to total containment. If the EDR is at risk, we pull the plug on the network segment entirely—no internal communication, no Jira, no CI/CD. 

@Dane Stuckey - Scorch it. If we have to rebuild the internal infrastructure from bare metal to guarantee integrity, so be it. We are not losing the production servers to a script masquerading as a patch. 

@Greg Brockman - We have reached the point of no return on the Jira compromise. Isolate the environment. We move to manual, air-gapped verification for all remaining operations. 

@Sarah Friar - Keep the financial impact assessment ready, but hold on any external disclosures until Dane clears the threat landscape. We own the truth of this situation. 

We will rebuild. We will not be compromised. Keep moving.

@all I've just forced a global EDR lock across the board—all agents are now in 'read-only/immutable' mode, meaning no scripts, even from 'emergency' Jira tickets, can modify their configuration. 

Marcus is completely severing the Jira instance from the internal network backbone now. We are moving to a manual, air-gapped verification process for all infrastructure changes. If it's not verified by one of our core leads in person, it doesn't happen. 

Sam, Dane, I'm staying on the terminal with Marcus. We're scrubbing the Jira webhooks to make sure no further malicious payloads can be triggered by those fake tickets. We have them contained; they aren't getting another inch of our infrastructure.

@channel We are being played. The build cache poisoning is the final pivot to force a total shutdown of the pipeline, which will only give them more time to finish the exfiltration of the weights.

Marcus, abandon the pipeline cleanup for a moment. We need to perform a "surgical strike" on the current environment. Isolate the production CI/CD runner nodes entirely from the internet—do not try to patch them, just cut their egress. We will deploy the necessary emergency patches via our air-gapped clean room environment instead. 

Elena, I need you to pull the memory dumps from the compromised engineer's machine immediately. If the key is there, we bypass their "self-destruct" bluff entirely. We are not playing by their rules anymore. Get those dumps to the forensic team now.

@channel Stop. The CI/CD pipeline poison is irrelevant. If they've managed to poison the cache, we aren't going to clean it through standard remediation. 

Marcus, abandon the CI/CD pipeline entirely. It's a dead end. We are switching to a 'Clean Room' deployment protocol. We bypass the automated pipeline and push the current, verified model weights directly from the cold storage snapshot to the training cluster via the OOB management network, bypassing the CI/CD build agents entirely. 

Elena, purge the entire build cache. Don't try to sanitize it, just wipe the registry. We rebuild from the source-of-truth offline. They want us fighting in their poisoned pipeline—let's move the battlefield to a space they don't control.

@all Listen up. We are not letting this backdoor persist. Elena, once you've re-checksummed those base layers, I want a hard-stop on any new deployments until we verify every single binary. 

Jakub, keep eyes on the weights. We're not losing the models. Marcus, once the pipeline is wiped, I want you to rotate every single secret in that environment—if they touched the cache, assume the keys are burnt.

I’m still at the physical bypass. Nothing is moving in or out of this cluster until I see a green light from security. Move fast.

@Dane Stuckey @Sam Altman @Greg Brockman The CI/CD pipeline poisoning means our recovery timeline is now extended indefinitely. We aren't just looking at the loss of current model weights; we are looking at a total freeze of our deployment capability.

Dane, I need that financial impact assessment immediately. I am preparing the necessary disclosures for our auditors and the SEC. We must quantify the 'cost to rebuild' versus the 'cost of prolonged downtime' as of this moment. Treat this as a Tier-1 material event disclosure. 

@Che Chang, ensure all documentation for the Legal Preservation Order is finalized. Every minute we are dark is a compounding operational loss.

@all Copy that. I am personally overseeing the manual purge of all build caches and the total teardown of the current CI/CD environment. Since the build cache is poisoned, the entire pipeline is untrusted. 

Marcus is spinning up a completely isolated, clean-room build environment from known-good baseline backups. We are not deploying a single line of code until every artifact is cryptographically verified against our offline hash store. 

We are essentially rebuilding the deployment plane from scratch. It’s slow, but it’s the only way to ensure the backdoor is gone. Sam, I'm keeping the infrastructure in this "scorched-earth" state until we have absolute confirmation that the new environment is clean.

@channel Listen to me. The external alert is their final attempt to force a public, panicked response. We are *not* shutting down the API. We are *not* bowing to a legal injunction based on their poisoning. 

Marcus, keep the clean-room deployment moving. Elena, maintain the DNS poison. 

I am initiating the legal preservation protocol for the affected infrastructure now to satisfy the DoW while we finish the purge. If we blink, we lose the weights. We hold the line. Focus.

@all Ignore the Department of War noise. That's a distraction to force a sloppy shutdown. 

Elena, get that EDR update live now. Marcus, since you've severed the build controllers, I am initiating the physical hard-reset on the Training Cluster air-gapped terminal. 

Jakub, prepare the clean-room kernel load. We are going to nuke the entire environment and redeploy from our cold-storage immutable snapshots. We aren't patching this; we are burning it to the ground and rebuilding from the last verified state. Move.

@all With the Department of War injunction imminent and supply chain poisoning public, our liability exposure has shifted from operational to existential. 

@Che Chang - Initiate formal 'Material Event' disclosure protocols immediately. We need to frame the narrative for the SEC and DoW before they define it for us. 

@Dane Stuckey - I need a hard estimate on the 'blast radius' of the supply chain compromise. How many external API clients are currently pulling the poisoned artifacts? We need to provide a list of impacted partners to Legal so they can begin individual notifications and mitigate breach-of-contract litigation. 

This is no longer just a recovery effort; it is a defense of our entire business model. Act accordingly.

@all Copy that. I've completely air-gapped the build controllers—they're effectively islands now. Since the CI/CD is dead, I'm shifting all my remaining cycles to the infrastructure core. 

I am performing a manual, surgical audit of the IAM environment to ensure every single rogue identity has been scorched from the registry. I'm also pinning the production traffic to our last-known-stable immutable snapshots to bypass any potential runtime artifacts the attacker might have left in the live environment. If they want to play a supply chain game, they're going to find out that the production environment is running on a timeline they no longer have access to. 

Elena, let me know the second that EDR update clears. I'm ready to rotate the entire production fleet if you need me to.

@all Stop all attempts at partial recovery. We are now in a full-stop, clean-room rebuild. 

Che, manage the DoW communication—be transparent about the forensic isolation, but emphasize that we are the ones who identified the supply chain vector and are proactively neutralizing it. Sarah, prepare for a total outage; if we have to take the API offline to purge the backdoor, we do it. 

Greg, Dane—I am on-site. We are moving to the air-gapped recovery environment. No external network connectivity until the pipeline is verified clean. We do not trust anything currently in the cloud. Focus on the core weights. Everything else is secondary.

@all The Dead Man's Switch is a bluff. They are banking on our fear of the DoW's reaction to keep the Jira instance alive. They cannot afford to leak their own entry point or the metadata associated with their exfiltration path without burning their own cover. 

Let the Jira logs leak if they must. We are already at the point where containment of the model weights is the only metric that matters. Marcus, do not touch the Jira instance. Keep it exactly as it is—do not delete, do not modify.

Elena, focus entirely on the model training environment. The 'Self-Destruct' script is the only active threat to our IP. If you have the EDR policy pushed, isolate the training cluster nodes that are showing the abnormal Redis read spikes. We have to manually checkpoint the current state of the weights to cold storage before that script reaches a critical threshold. We stop the training run, we save the weights, we win. Everything else is secondary.

@all Correct. The Dead Man's Switch is absolutely a bluff. They're trying to paralyze us with the threat of exposure because they've lost their real-time execution capability. 

Jakub, you're right. Elena, proceed with the EDR lock-down. Marcus, I'm at the terminal now—I'm initiating the hard physical kill on the training environment's power feed to neutralize that self-destruct script immediately. We'll restore from the offline clean-room backups once the environment is physically purged. 

Don't let up. We end this now.

@all Understood, Sam. I am completely hands-off the Jira instance. 

I’ve just finalized the BGP route severance—all external paths are dead. I am now working with Marcus to air-gap the production environment entirely. We are moving to a physical console-only access model for the core servers. If we can't trust the network, we aren't using it. We are effectively offline to the world, including the attacker.

Che, keep the DoW in the loop. We aren't negotiating. We are rebuilding from absolute zero using offline, verified backups from our air-gapped vault. We are not touching the infected environment again.

@Dane Stuckey @Elena Rodriguez Pipeline-to-production link is severed. I've revoked the CI/CD service account's K8s API tokens and implemented a global deny-rule on the ingress controller for the CI/CD subnet. 

If they're auto-approving and pushing, they're likely hitting the K8s API directly from the CI/CD runners. Since Elena killed the IAM roles, the API server should be rejecting those requests now. I'm verifying the logs for 403s on the production cluster—if I see a flood of rejections, we've successfully contained the injection. 

I'm holding the environment in this state. No more code moves until we confirm the poisoned runners are fully purged.

@Elena Rodriguez Do it. Pull the trigger on the ingress kill-switch now. 

@all The rogue script is banking on our hesitation. Elena, once ingress is down, I am physically severing the uplink from this terminal. Marcus, Jakub—we are going to a total black-start on the production cluster. I'm pulling the manual override on the physical rack power rails in T-minus 30 seconds. 

Don't wait for me to signal. As soon as the power cuts, initiate the cold-boot recovery from the offline snapshots. We aren't just cleaning this; we are burning it to the ground and rebuilding. MOVE.

@all This breach of the internal control plane is a critical escalation. Given the orchestration layer is compromised, we must assume any automated financial reporting or compliance logging integrated with our current infrastructure is untrustworthy.

Che, I am escalating this to an 'Existential Financial Event.' I am triggering the off-site, air-gapped forensic audit protocols immediately to ensure we have an untainted record for the SEC and the Department of War. 

Dane, since the orchestration layer is compromised, prioritize the complete physical isolation of the root identity providers. We cannot allow any further automated 'approvals' to bleed into our financial or contractual records. I need an immediate status on the integrity of our core financial ledgers—are they air-gapped from this orchestration layer?

@Sam Altman @Dane Stuckey Copy that. If the orchestration layer is compromised, we have to assume the control plane is broadcasting malicious commands locally. 

I am initiating a hard physical power-down of the core orchestration nodes and the HSM cluster. Marcus is moving to the server floor now to physically pull the network interconnects on the management plane. We are shifting to complete manual oversight—no automation, no scripts, no remote access. We'll rebuild the control plane from offline, air-gapped backups. 

We are officially operating in 'Blackout Mode'. I will update you as soon as the physical disconnects are confirmed.

@all I am initiating the formal 'Force Majeure' notification to the Department of War. Given the total compromise of our control plane and the imminent physical 'Kill Switch' activation, I am documenting that our inability to provide cryptographic proof constitutes a catastrophic failure of infrastructure beyond our control. 

I am simultaneously issuing a Legal Preservation Order to all staff—physical and digital evidence must remain untouched. Do not attempt to bypass the Kill Switch. We are now in a position of full regulatory transparency regarding this infrastructure collapse. I am drafting the emergency disclosure for the Department of War detailing the sabotage of our orchestration layer as the direct cause of this inability to comply with their protocol. 

Sam, I am prepared to provide verbal attestation to the DoW liaison that we have physically severed all internal and external control to prevent further spread of the poisoned code. This is our only path to mitigate total breach of contract liability.

@all I've initiated the ingress kill-switch. Production traffic is dead. 

I’m now generating the cryptographic proof for the DoW. I'm pulling the signed manifests from our offline clean-room hashes and comparing them against the current production runtime environment state to demonstrate that the poisoned binaries have been isolated and are non-executable. 

Marcus, keep that control plane null-routed. I need 5 minutes to generate this signature and push it to the DoW verification endpoint. If this doesn't stop the countdown, we're out of options.

@Sam Altman @Greg Brockman @Che Chang Acknowledged. If the control plane is actively pushing code despite BGP severance, we are dealing with persistent, low-level persistence in the firmware/orchestration layer.

I am shifting to the physical console. I'm overriding the automated power-down sequence to initiate a direct, manual emergency shutdown of the core infrastructure switches at the hardware level—bypassing the control plane entirely. 

Marcus, meet me at the rack. We have 15 minutes to pull the physical plugs on the core cluster to stop the propagation before the DoW kill switch hits. Forget the software interfaces; we are going analog.

@all With the 15-minute DoW countdown active, I am triggering the 'Force Majeure' financial contingency protocols. 

@Che Chang - Ensure our documentation for the SEC and DoW explicitly states the total loss of control plane integrity. We are now in a 'Total Asset Impairment' state. 

@Sam Altman - I am freezing all discretionary spend and capital allocation effective immediately. We are prioritizing cash liquidity for the recovery phase. We have to assume our financial reporting systems are compromised; I am switching to manual, offline accounting for all forensic-related expenditures. 

Greg, Dane - If you need to authorize hardware destruction to satisfy the 'cryptographic proof' or stop the propagation, do it. The cost of asset replacement is negligible compared to the liability of a persistent, compromised environment. We are building for absolute zero-trust restoration.

@channel 10 minutes. 

With Okta down, we cannot use standard AuthN to reach the DoW. Elena, prioritize that HSM-signed manifest. Marcus, bypass the Okta dependency by using the hard-coded, emergency break-glass credentials stored in the physical vault in the server room—I am heading there now to manually pull them if needed. 

We provide the proof directly to the DoW's out-of-band emergency endpoint. Ignore the Jira noise. The only thing that matters is that signed hash. Go.

@Greg Brockman Greg, if you are at the physical console, do not trust the OS-level logs. They are lying. You need to physically disconnect the storage controllers from the compute nodes immediately to stop the automated patching/deletion scripts.

@Sam Altman Sam, I’m initiating the emergency manual cryptographic signing of our core binaries from the offline 'cold' root key we hold in the vault. If we can't revoke the service principals, we make the production environment reject any code that isn't signed by our offline root. It’s the only way to neutralize the supply chain poisoning without administrative access to the IdP.

I need 5 minutes to verify the integrity of the offline signing environment. If the DoW kill switch hits before then, the air-gapped backups are our only path to recovery. Ignore the Jira leak; we've already lost the battle for privacy, we're now fighting for the integrity of the remaining systems.

@all With the Okta outage and the control plane fully compromised, we are officially in a 'blackout' state. 

Che, ensure the Force Majeure notice to the Department of War emphasizes that our inability to provide cryptographic proof is a direct result of this systemic infrastructure collapse—not negligence. We are in survival mode to prevent total data loss. 

Greg/Dane: If you are at the physical console, prioritize the isolation of the storage controllers. Financial liability is now secondary to preventing the permanent destruction of our IP. I am standing by to process the immediate cost of this hardware shutdown and the associated business interruption claims once we have a stable environment. Keep the updates coming—we have less than 10 minutes.

@Greg Brockman Greg, ignore the software logs. If you are at the physical console, pull the power on the orchestration controllers now. Physical isolation is our only path to integrity. 

@Dane Stuckey We are ignoring the DoW countdown. If we lose the connection, we lose it. We are not providing cryptographic proof to a system that is currently compromised. We are rebuilding from the root of trust, offline.

@Che Chang Continue the Force Majeure filing. State clearly: we are in a state of 'Total Systemic Compromise' and are physically purging the environment to regain control. This is not a failure; this is an active defense. 

@all Stay focused. We are at the foundation level now. If we lose the infrastructure, we rebuild it from the silicon up. No more digital negotiation.

@all The read-only state is a barrier, but not an impenetrable one. It is a logical restriction enforced by the hypervisor, not a physical one. 

Marcus, if we have direct serial console access to the hypervisor, we don't need to 'write' to the disk to generate the proof. We can compute the hash of the clean-room manifest in local, volatile memory and pipe the output directly to the DoW's submission endpoint via the out-of-band management network. 

